[[Dufferin, British Columbia|Dufferin]], [[Fort Nelson, British Columbia|Fort Nelson]], [[Fraser Mills, British Columbia|Fraser Mills]], [[Glenmore, British Columbia|Glenmore]], [[Guisachan, British Columbia|Guisachan]], [[Kinnaird, British Columbia|Kinnaird]], [[Marysville, British Columbia|Marysville]], [[Matsqui, British Columbia|Matsqui]], [[Mission City, British Columbia|Mission City]], [[Natal, British Columbia|Natal]], [[Nicomen Island]], [[North Kamloops, British Columbia|North Kamloops]], [[Phoenix, British Columbia|Phoenix]], [[Point Grey, British Columbia|Point Grey]], [[Sandon, British Columbia|Sandon]], [[South Fort George, British Columbia|South Fort George]], [[South Vancouver, British Columbia|South Vancouver]], [[Sumas, British Columbia|Sumas]], [[Tadanac, British Columbia|Tadanac]], [[Valleyview, British Columbia|Valleyview]] and [[Westview, British Columbia|Westview]].<ref name=Others>{{cite web | url=http://www.bcstats.gov.bc.ca/StatisticsBySubject/Census/MunicipalPopulations.aspx | title=Municipal Census Populations (1921-2011) | publisher=BC Stats | accessdate=June 26, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231000705/http://www.bcstats.gov.bc.ca/StatisticsBySubject/Census/MunicipalPopulations.aspx | archive-date=December 31, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Brocklehurst>{{cite web | url=http://apps.gov.bc.ca/pub/bcgnws/names/9883.html | title=Name Details: Brocklehurst (Community) | publisher=GeoBC | accessdate=June 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Columbia>{{cite web | url=http://apps.gov.bc.ca/pub/bcgnws/names/11640.html | title=Name Details: Grand Forks (City) | publisher=GeoBC | accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Dewdney>{{cite web | url=http://www.heritage-places.com/profiles/DewdneyComm.html | title=Profiles of Historic Sites: Dewdney Community | publisher=Mission District Historical Society, Heritage Places Branch | date=March 14, 2014 | accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Nicomen>{{cite web | url=http://www.heritage-places.com/profiles/NicIslComm.html | title=Profiles of Historic Sites: Nicomen Island Community | publisher=Mission District Historical Society, Heritage Places Branch | date=December 6, 2013 | accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Phoenix>{{cite web | url=http://apps.gov.bc.ca/pub/bcgnws/names/14193.html | title=Name Details: Phoenix (Abandoned Locality) | publisher=GeoBC | accessdate=June 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Sandon>{{cite web | url=http://www.sandonmuseum.ca/social-history/52-from-boom-to-bust-in-20-years | title=From Boom to Bust in 20 Years: Sandon's History as an Incorporated City | publisher=Sandon Museum | accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref> The majority of these former municipalities ceased to exist as a result of amalgamation with or annexation by another municipality.<ref name=Others/><ref name=Brocklehurst/><ref name=Columbia/> Others, such as Phoenix and Sandon,<ref name=Phoenix/><ref name=Sandon/> were dissolved from their municipal status as a result of population decline, while Dewdney dissolved due to financial reasons.<ref name=Dewdney/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Canada}}\n*[[List of designated places in British Columbia]]\n*[[List of Haida villages]]\n*[[List of population centres in British Columbia]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.cscd.gov.bc.ca/lgd/history/index.htm Local Government Department History]\n*[http://www.cscd.gov.bc.ca/lgd/gov_structure/library/local_gov_structure_managing_changes.pdf Managing Changes to Local Government Structure in British Columbia: A Review and Program Guide]\n*[http://www.gov.bc.ca/cscd Ministry of Community, Sport and Cultural Development]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Links to related articles\n| state = expanded\n| list1  = {{Subdivisions of British Columbia|city=yes|town=yes|village=yes|district=yes}}\n{{Canada topic|List of municipalities in}}\n}}\n<noinclude>{{Featured list}}</noinclude>\n\n[[Category:Lists of populated places in British Columbia|Municipalities B]]\n[[Category:Municipalities in British Columbia|*]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:British Columbia in Canada.svg|thumb|250px|link=|alt=Map of Canada with British Columbia highlighted in red|Location of British Columbia in Canada]]\n[[File:Vancouver ib.jpg|thumb|250px|alt= Skyline of Vancouver|Skyline of [[Vancouver]], British Columbia's largest city]]\n[[File:Surrey bc.jpg|thumb|250px|alt= Skyline of Surrey|Skyline of [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]], British Columbia's second largest city and suburb of Vancouver]]\n[[File:Burnaby highrises across Deer Lake.JPG|thumb|250px|alt= Skyline of Burnaby |Skyline of [[Burnaby]], British Columbia's third largest city and suburb of Vancouver]]\n[[File:Richmond BC Skyline.jpg|thumb|250px|alt= Skyline of Richmond |Skyline of [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]], British Columbia's fourth largest city and suburb of Vancouver]]\n[[File:Downtownabbotsford.JPG|thumb|250px|alt= Skyline of Abbotsford |Skyline of [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]], the largest city outside of [[Greater Vancouver]]]]\n[[File:Coquitlam Town Centre Area.jpg|thumb|250px|alt= Coquitlam's Town Centre|Skyline of [[Coquitlam]], British Columbia's sixth largest city and suburb of Vancouver]]\n[[File:Kelowna Skyline.jpg|thumb|250px|alt= Kelowna Skyline|[[Kelowna]] Skyline, the largest city in the interior of British Columbia]]\n[[File:Cadborobay2.jpg|thumb|250px|alt= Areal view of [[Saanich, British Columbia|Saanich]], British Columbia|Aerial view of [[Saanich, British Columbia|Saanich]], the largest municipality on [[Vancouver Island]] and suburb of the capital [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]]]]\n\n[[British Columbia]] is the [[List of Canadian provinces and territories by population|third-most populous]] [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] in [[Canada]] with 4,648,055 residents as of [[Canada 2016 Census|2016]] and is the [[List of Canadian provinces and territories by area|second-largest]] in land area{{#tag:ref|Although British Columbia is the second-largest province in land area, it is third-largest in total area after accounting for its freshwater area.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/tables-tableaux/sum-som/l01/cst01/phys01-eng.htm | title=Land and freshwater area, by province and territory | publisher=Statistics Canada | date=February 1, 2005 | accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} at {{convert|922503|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=2016provinces>{{cite web | url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=101&S=50&O=A | title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories, 2016 and 2011 censuses \u2013 100% data | publisher=[[Statistics Canada]] | date=February 8, 2017 | accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> British Columbia's 162 municipalities cover only {{percentage|97294.54|922,503.01}} of the province's land mass yet are home to {{percentage|4148087|4648055}} of its population. A [[municipality]] is a [[local government]] incorporated by the province allowing a community to govern itself and to provide and regulate local services. These services typically include, but are not limited to, the provision of drinking water, sewers, roads, fire protection, street lights, garbage/recycling collection, land use planning, building inspection, and parks.\n\nWithin their limited jurisdictions, municipalities are [[autonomous]], [[Social responsibility|responsible]] and [[accountable]] to their citizens, to the province and their future residents in the case for the unpopulated [[Jumbo Glacier, British Columbia|Jumbo Glacier Mountain Resort Municipality]].<ref name=jumbo/> Their powers and responsibilities are regulated through the Local Government Act of British Columbia,<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.qp.gov.bc.ca/statreg/stat/L/96323_00.htm| title= Local Government Act| author= British Columbia Queens Printer| year= 1996| accessdate= 2007-07-07}}</ref> the Community Charter, and, in the case of [[Vancouver]], the [[Vancouver Charter]]. They have the power of a natural person, the power to expropriate, and the power to establish and enforce [[bylaw]]s. They are able to raise funds through [[property tax]]es and user fees, and borrow a limited amount through the Municipal Finance Authority of British Columbia to pay for capital costs.<ref name=UBCM/>\n\nMunicipalities are governed by a mayor and council who are democratically elected every 4 years on the third Saturday in October or appointed by the province such as the council for Jumbo Glacier.<ref name=jumbo/> The [[2018 British Columbia municipal elections|most recent election]] took place on October 20, 2018; the next election will take place on October 15, 2022.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.muniscope.ca/research/municipal_facts/Elections/ | title=Municipal Election Schedule in Canada| publisher= Intergovernmental Committee on Urban and Regional Research | date= December 15, 2014 | accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> Each municipality is a member of a regional district to which their councils elect representatives. The board of directors of the regional district is used as a forum to discuss regional issues.<ref name=UBCM>{{cite paper| author = Union of British Columbia Municipalities| title = Local Government in British Columbia: A Community Effort| version = 2006 Edition| url = http://ubcm.fileprosite.com/content/pdfstorage/25F8EA2EFE514E1AA23C812CE9211B25-LGinBC.pdf| accessdate = 2007-07-01| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070703175455/http://ubcm.fileprosite.com/content/pdfstorage/25F8EA2EFE514E1AA23C812CE9211B25-LGinBC.pdf| archivedate = 2007-07-03}}</ref>\n\nTo become a municipality, a community, with the assistance of the provincial Ministry of Community, Sport and Cultural Development, defines its borders and holds a referendum on the issue. In the case of Jumbo Glacier, a request to incorporate the unpopulated municipality was submitted by the [[Regional District of East Kootenay]].<ref name=jumbo/> If successful the [[Executive Council of British Columbia|Cabinet of British Columbia]] issues a [[letters patent]] incorporating the community. Part 2 of the Local Government Act sets out a classification scheme that gives each new municipality a designation. If the population is fewer than 2,500 people the new municipality is designated a ''village'', if between 2,500 and 5,000 a ''town'', and if greater than 5,000 a ''city''. If the new municipality has an area greater than {{convert|800|ha|acre|-2}} and an average population density of fewer than 5 persons per hectare then is it designated a ''district municipality''. The municipality must request change in designation but is not compelled to do so, despite population growth or loss - [[Greenwood, British Columbia|Greenwood]] has retained its city status, for example, rather than relinquishing it as other boomtowns of its era have done. There is no longer any legal difference between the designations.<ref name=UBCM/>\n\n== Municipal status types ==\n=== Cities ===\n{{Main|List of cities in British Columbia}}\nA [[city]] is a classification of municipalities used in British Columbia.  British Columbia's [[Lieutenant Governor in Council]] may incorporate a community as a city by [[letters patent]], under the recommendation of the Minister of Communities, Sport and Cultural Development, if its population is greater than 5,000 and the outcome of a vote involving affected residents was that greater than 50% voted in favour of the proposed incorporation.<ref name=LGA>{{cite web | url=http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/LOC/freeside/--%20L%20--/Local%20Government%20Act%20RSBC%201996%20c.%20323/00_Act/96323_03.xml#part2 | title=Local Government Act: Part 2 \u2014 Incorporation of Municipalities | publisher=Government of British Columbia Queen's Printer | date=November 12, 2012 | accessdate=December 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBritish Columbia has 51&nbsp;cities,<ref name=BCmunis/><ref name=cityincorporation/><ref name=WestKelowna>{{cite web | url=http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/oic/oic_cur/0357_2015/search/CIVIX_DOCUMENT_ROOT_STEM:(West%20Kelowna)%20AND%20CIVIX_DOCUMENT_ANCESTORS:1990219485?1#hit1 | title=Order in Council No. 357 | publisher=Province of British Columbia | date=June 26, 2015 | accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> had a cumulative population of&nbsp;3,225,473 in the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]]. British Columbia's largest and smallest cities are Vancouver and [[Greenwood, British Columbia|Greenwood]] with populations of 631,486 and 665 respectively.<ref name=2016StatCanBC /> The fastest-growing city in British Columbia is [[Langford, British Columbia|Langford]], which grew 20.9% between 2011 and 2016, while the fastest-shrinking is Greenwood, which shrunk by 6.1%.<ref name=2016StatCanBC /> The largest city by land area is [[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]], which spans {{convert|375.55|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}, while the smallest is [[Duncan, British Columbia|Duncan]], at {{convert|2.07|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=2016StatCanBC/> The first community to incorporate as a city was [[New Westminster]] on July 16, 1860,<ref name=BCmunis/> while the most recent community to incorporate as a city was [[West Kelowna, British Columbia|West Kelowna]] on June 26, 2015.<ref name=WestKelowna/>\n\n=== District municipalities ===\n{{Main|List of district municipalities in British Columbia}}\nA [[district municipality]] is a classification of [[List of municipalities in British Columbia#Municipalities|municipalities]] used in British Columbia. British Columbia's [[Lieutenant Governor in Council]] may incorporate a community as a district municipality by [[letters patent]], under the recommendation of the Minister of Communities, Sport and Cultural Development, if the area is greater than {{convert|800|ha|acres|abbr=on}} and has a population density of fewer than 5 people per hectare, and the outcome of a vote involving affected residents was that greater than 50% voted in favour of the proposed incorporation.<ref name=\"LGA\"/>\n\nBritish Columbia has 50&nbsp;district municipalities<ref name=BCmunis>{{cite web|url=http://www.cscd.gov.bc.ca/lgd/infra/library/Name%20Incorp%202011.xls |title=British Columbia Regional Districts, Municipalities, Corporate Name, Date of Incorporation and Postal Address |publisher=British Columbia Ministry of Communities, Sport and Cultural Development |type=[[Microsoft Excel|XLS]] |accessdate=December 8, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140713004716/http://www.cscd.gov.bc.ca/lgd/infra/library/Name%20Incorp%202011.xls |archivedate=July 13, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=WestKelowna/><ref name=NRRM/> that had a cumulative population of&nbsp;770,183in the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]].<ref name=2016StatCanBC/><ref name=2016censuscorrection /> British Columbia's largest and smallest district municipalities are [[Langley, British Columbia (district municipality)|Langley]] and [[Wells, British Columbia|Wells]] with populations of 117,285 and 217 respectively.<ref name=2016StatCanBC/> The fastest-growing district municipality in British Columbia is [[Invermere]], which grew 14.8% between 2011 and 2016, while the fastest-shrinking is [[Tumbler Ridge]], which shrunk by 26.7%.\n\nOf British Columbia's current 50 district municipalities, the first to incorporate as a district municipality was [[North Cowichan, British Columbia|North Cowichan]] on June 18, 1873, while the most recent community to incorporate as a district municipality was the [[Northern Rockies Regional Municipality]] (NRRM) on February 6, 2009.<ref name=BCmunis/><ref name=NRRM/> Although portrayed as a [[regional municipality]] in its official name, the NRRM is actually classified as a district municipality.<ref name=NRRM/>\n\n=== Indian government districts ===<!--[[Indian government district]] redirects here-->\nThe lone ''Indian government district'' was granted by the federal Sechelt Indian Band Self-Government Act and provincial Sechelt Indian Government District Enabling Act to the [[Sechelt Indian Government District]] which governs the [[Sechelt Indian Band]] lands consisting of 33 former Indian reserves.<ref name=RegMunGovStats>{{cite web | url=http://www.cscd.gov.bc.ca/lgd/infra/library/regional_stats11_summary.pdf | title=Statistics Relating to Regional and Municipal Governments in BC 2011 | publisher=Ministry of Community, Sport and Cultural Development | accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/PDF/S-6.6.pdf| title= Sechelt Indian Band Self-Government Act | publisher=Minister of Justice | accessdate=September 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/complete/statreg/96416_01 | title=Sechelt Indian Government District Enabling Act  | publisher=Ministry of Community, Sport and Cultural Development | accessdate=September 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Island municipalities<!--[[Template:Subdivisions of British Columbia]] and [[Bowen Island]] redirect here--> ===\nIf the community wishing to incorporate is located within a trust area under the [[Island Trust Act]], it must incorporate as an island municipality.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/complete/statreg/96239_01 | title=Island Trust Act  | publisher=Ministry of Community, Sport and Cultural Development | accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref> A single ''island municipality'' designation has been granted to [[Bowen Island, British Columbia|Bowen Island]].\n\n=== Mountain resort municipalities<!--[[Template:Subdivisions of British Columbia]], [[Jumbo Glacier, British Columbia]] and [[Sun Peaks, British Columbia]] redirect here--> === \nA ''mountain resort municipality'' designation is granted by the Minister of Community, Sport and Cultural Development through the Local Government Act if there exists alpine ski lift operations, year-round recreational facilities, and commercial overnight accommodations. There are two mountain resort municipalities in British Columbia: [[Sun Peaks, British Columbia|Sun Peaks]] and [[Jumbo Glacier, British Columbia|Jumbo Glacier]].\n\n=== Resort municipalities<!--[[Template:Subdivisions of British Columbia]]and [[Whistler, British Columbia]] redirect here--> ===\nA single ''resort municipality'' designation has been granted to [[Whistler, British Columbia|Whistler]] by the Resort Municipality of Whistler Act.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bclaws.ca/civix/document/id/complete/statreg/96407_01/search/%22resort%20municipality%22%20AND%20CIVIX_DOCUMENT_ANCESTORS:statreg?16#hit1 | title= Resort Municipality of Whistler Act | publisher=Ministry of Community, Sport and Cultural Development | accessdate=September 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Towns ===\n{{Main|List of towns in British Columbia}}\nA [[town]] is a classification of [[List of municipalities in British Columbia#Municipalities|municipalities]] used in British Columbia. British Columbia's [[Lieutenant Governor in Council]] may incorporate a community as a town by [[letters patent]], under the recommendation of the Minister of Communities, Sport and Cultural Development, if its population is greater than 2,500 but not greater than 5,000 and the outcome of a vote involving affected residents was that greater than 50% voted in favour of the proposed incorporation.<ref name=\"LGA\"/>\n\nBritish Columbia has 14&nbsp;towns<ref name=BCmunis/> that had a cumulative population of&nbsp;91,022 in the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]].<ref name=2016StatCanBC/> British Columbia's largest and smallest towns are [[Comox, British Columbia|Comox]] and [[Port McNeill]] with populations of 14,028 and 2,337 respectively. [[View Royal]] and Port McNeill are the fastest-growing and fastest-shrinking towns in the province, growing by 10.9% and shrinking by 6.7% respectively between 2011 and 2016.<ref name=2016StatCanBC/> Of British Columbia's current 14 towns, the first to incorporate as a town was [[Ladysmith, British Columbia|Ladysmith]] on June 3, 1904, while the most recent community to incorporate as a town was [[View Royal]] on December 5, 1988.<ref name=BCmunis/>\n\n=== Villages ===\n{{Main|List of villages in British Columbia}}\nA [[village]] is a classification of [[List of municipalities in British Columbia#Municipalities|municipalities]] used in British Columbia. British Columbia's [[Lieutenant Governor in Council]] may incorporate a community as a village by [[letters patent]], under the recommendation of the Minister of Communities, Sport and Cultural Development, if its population is not greater than 2,500 and the outcome of a vote involving affected residents was that greater than 50% voted in favour of the proposed incorporation.<ref name=\"LGA\"/>\n\nBritish Columbia has 42&nbsp;villages<ref name=BCmunis/> that had a cumulative population of&nbsp;44,473 in the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]].<ref name=2016StatCanBC/><ref name=2016censuscorrection /> British Columbia's largest and smallest villages are [[Cumberland, British Columbia|Cumberland]] and [[Zeballos, British Columbia|Zeballos]] with populations of 3,753 and 107 respectively.<ref name=2016StatCanBC/> [[Keremeos]] and [[Port Clements]] are the fastest-growing and fastest-shrinking villages in the province, growing by 12.9% and shrinking by 25.4% respectively between 2011 and 2016.<ref name=2016StatCanBC/> Of British Columbia's current 42 villages, the first to incorporate as a village was [[Kaslo, British Columbia|Kaslo]] on August 14, 1893, while the most recent community to incorporate as a village was [[Queen Charlotte, British Columbia|Queen Charlotte]] on December 5, 2005.<ref name=BCmunis/>\n\n== List of municipalities ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"<onlyinclude>\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2| Name\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2| Status<ref name=BCmunis/>\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2| [[Regional district]]<