nse. Only English and French were counted as official languages in the census. Figures shown are for the number of single language responses and the percentage of total single-language responses.<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/topics/RetrieveProductTable.cfm?ALEVEL=3&APATH=3&CATNO=&DETAIL=0&DIM=&DS=99&FL=0&FREE=0&GAL=0&GC=99&GK=NA&GRP=1&IPS=&METH=0&ORDER=1&PID=89201&PTYPE=88971&RL=0&S=1&ShowAll=No&StartRow=1&SUB=701&Temporal=2006&Theme=70&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&GID=838093 Detailed Mother Tongue (186), Knowledge of Official Languages (5), Age Groups (17A) and Sex (3) (2006 Census)]</ref>\n\n==Visible minorities and Aboriginals==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Visible minority and Aboriginal population ([[Canada 2016 Census]])\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Population group!! Population !! % of total population\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''[[European Canadian|European]]''' || '''4,120''' || '''{{Percentage | 4120 | 35580 | 1 }}'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" | [[Visible minority]] group<br /><small>Source:<ref>[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-591/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=62&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Nunavut&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=], Community Profiles from the 2006 Census, Statistics Canada - Province/Territory</ref></small> || [[South Asia]]n || 115 || {{Percentage | 115 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]] || 75 || {{Percentage | 75 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Black Canadians|Black]] || 330 || {{Percentage | 330 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Filipino Canadian|Filipino]] || 230 || {{Percentage | 230 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadian|Latin American]] || 40 || {{Percentage | 40 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Arab Canadians|Arab]] || 40 || {{Percentage | 40 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asia]]n || 30 || {{Percentage | 30 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Western Asia|West Asian]] || 10 || {{Percentage | 10 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Korean Canadian|Korean]] || 10 || {{Percentage | 10 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Japanese Canadians|Japanese]] || 10 || {{Percentage | 10 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| Visible minority, n.i.e. || 20 || {{Percentage | 20 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Multiracial|Multiple]] visible minority || 10 || {{Percentage | 10 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''Total visible minority population'''|| '''905''' || '''{{Percentage | 905 | 35580 | 1 }}'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] group<br /><small>Source:<ref>[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-594/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=62&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Nunavut&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=], Aboriginal Population Profile from the 2006 Census, Statistics Canada - Province/Territory</ref></small> || [[First Nations]] || 190 || {{Percentage | 190 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] || 165 || {{Percentage | 165 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| [[Inuit]] || 30,135 || {{Percentage | 30135 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| Aboriginal, n.i.e. || 10 || {{Percentage | 10 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| Multiple Aboriginal identity || 55 || {{Percentage | 55 | 35580 | 1 }}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''Total Aboriginal population''' || '''30,555''' || '''{{Percentage | 30555 | 35580 | 1 }}'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''''Total population''''' || '''''35,580''''' || '''''100%'''''\n|}\n\nThe majority of Nunavut residents identifying as White (61%), First Nations (58%), Metis (58%), and Visible Minority (65%) live in the capital city of Iqaluit.\n\n==Religion==\nThe dominant religion in Nunavut is [[Christianity]]; [[Catholicism]], [[Anglicanism]] and [[Pentecostalism]] are highly prevalent.\n\nTraditionally, [[Shamanism among Eskimo peoples|Inuit shamanism]] has always been a [[taboo]] subject in [[Inuit culture]], not openly talked about. Shamans didn't make it known they were one, but the group or clan they were a part of knew.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | Religious beliefs in the [[Canada 2001 Census|2001 census]]<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=62&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Nunavut&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=&GeoCode=62 | title= Canada Census 2001 | author= StatCan | authorlink= Statistics Canada | year= | month= | accessdate= 28 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n! Religion\n! Adherents\n! % of the population\n|-\n|[[Roman Catholicism in Canada|Catholic]] ||6,215||23.30\n|-\n|[[Protestantism|Protestant]] ||17,785||66.69\n|-\n|[[Orthodox Christianity|Christian Orthodox]] ||20||0.07\n|-\n|[[List of Christian denominations|Other Christian]]||835||3.13\n|-\n|[[Islam in Canada|Muslim]] ||25||0.09\n|-\n|[[History of the Jews in Canada|Jewish]] ||10||0.04\n|-\n|[[Buddhism in Canada|Buddhist]] ||15||0.06\n|-\n|[[Eastern religions]]||60||0.22\n|-\n|Other religions||40||0.15\n|-\n|[[Irreligion|No religious affiliation]]||1,655||6.21\n|-\n|Total||26,670||100.00\n|}\n\n==Migration==\nWhile there is some [[Interprovincial migration in Canada|internal migration]] from the rest of Canada to Nunavut (usually on a temporary basis), there is very little external migration from outside of Canada to Nunavut.\n\nThe 2006 census counted a total of only about 450 immigrants in Nunavut, including about 80 from the United Kingdom, about 40 each from the United States and the Philippines, about 30 from Germany, about 20 each from China and India, and just over 10 each from Jamaica and South Africa.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/topics/RetrieveProductTable.cfm?ALEVEL=3&APATH=3&CATNO=&DETAIL=0&DIM=&DS=99&FL=0&FREE=0&GAL=0&GC=99&GK=NA&GRP=1&IPS=&METH=0&ORDER=1&PID=89424&PTYPE=88971&RL=0&S=1&ShowAll=No&StartRow=1&SUB=0&Temporal=2006&Theme=72&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&GID=838093 |title=Statistics Canada catalogue no. 97-557-XCB2006007 |year=2007}}</ref>\n\nA total of 4,940 people moved to Nunavut from other parts of Canada between 1996 and 2006 while 5,615 people moved in the opposite direction. These movements resulted in a net influx of 355 from Newfoundland and Labrador; and a net outmigration of 355 to Alberta, 295 to the Northwest Territories, 235 to Ontario and 160 to Quebec. There was a net outmigration of 150 francophones from Nunavut to Quebec during this period. (All net inter-provincial and official minority movements of more than 100 persons are given).<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/topics/RetrieveProductTable.cfm?ALEVEL=3&APATH=3&CATNO=&DETAIL=0&DIM=&DS=99&FL=0&FREE=0&GAL=0&GC=99&GK=NA&GRP=1&IPS=&METH=0&ORDER=1&PID=89180&PTYPE=88971&RL=0&S=1&ShowAll=No&StartRow=1&SUB=0&Temporal=2006&Theme=71&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&GID=614148\n|title=Statistics Canada catalogue no. 97-556-XCB2006010 |year=2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census01/products/standard/themes/RetrieveProductTable.cfm?Temporal=2001&PID=55550&APATH=3&GID=517769&METH=1&PTYPE=55440&THEME=42&FOCUS=0&AID=0&PLACENAME=0&PROVINCE=0&SEARCH=0&GC=0&GK=0&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&FL=0&RL=0&FREE=0\n|title=Statistics Canada catalogue no. 97-F0008-XCB2001005 |year=2002}}</ref>\n\n==Age==\nThe median age in Nunavut is 25.1 years, according to the 2016 census.  This is significantly younger than the median age of Canada (41.2 years).  Those aged 65 years and over account for 3.8% of the population.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of communities in Nunavut]]\n*[[Demographics of Canada]]\n*[[Population of Canada by province and territory]]\n\n==Notes==\n*{{note|a|a}}Iqaluit is both the capital of Nunavut and the regional centre for the [[Qikiqtaaluk Region]], while Rankin Inlet and Cambridge Bay are the regional centres for the [[Kivalliq Region|Kivalliq]] and [[Kitikmeot Region, Nunavut|Kitikmeot Regions]] respectively.\n*{{note|b|b}}Official language of Nunavut\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Canada}}\n{{Nunavut}}\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Canada topic|Demographics of}}\n\n[[Category:Demographics of Canada by province or territory|Nunavut]]\n[[Category:Nunavut society]]\n", "text_old": "{{Canada provinces map|align=right|prefix=Demographics of|map=NU-Canada-territory.png|caption=Demographics of Canada's provinces and territories}}\n'''[[Nunavut]]''' is a [[provinces and territories of Canada|territory]] of [[Canada]]. It has a land area of {{convert|1,877,787.62|km2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"stats2011\">{{Cite web| url= http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=62&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Nunavut&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=62 | title= Canada Census 2011 | author= StatCan | authorlink= Statistics Canada | year= | month= | accessdate= 12 February 2017}}</ref> In the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 census]] the population was 35,944,<ref name=\"stats2011\"/> up 12.7% from the [[Canada 2011 Census|2011 census]] figure of 31,906.<ref name=\"stats2006\">{{Cite web | url= http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census16/data/profiles/community/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=62&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Nunavut&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=&GeoCode=62 | title= Canada Census 2016 | author= StatCan | authorlink= Statistics Canada | year=  | month=  | accessdate= 12 February 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2006, the latest year for which figures are available, 24,630 people identified themselves as [[Inuit]] (84.1% of the total population), 100 as [[First Nations|North American Indian]] (0.3%), 130 [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] (0.4%) and 4,410 as non-aboriginal (15.1%).<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-594/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=62&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Nunavut&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=62 | title= 2006 Aboriginal Population Profile | author= StatCan | authorlink= Statistics Canada | year= 2006 | month= | accessdate= 2008-04-27}}</ref>\n\nNunavut's small and sparse population makes it unlikely the territory will be granted provincial status in the foreseeable future, although this may change if the [[Yukon]], which is marginally less populous, becomes a province.\n\n==Historical population==\n{{Graph:Chart\n | width = 950\n | height= 450\n | type = line\n | interpolate =\n | xType = date\n | xAxisAngle = -40\n | yAxisTitle = Population\n | yGrid = \n | linewidth = 2\n | x = 1996, 2001, 2006, 2011, 2016\n | y = 24730, 26745, 29474, 31906, 35944\n | colors = #9370db\n}}\n{{Historical populations\n|align       = centre\n|footnote    = <ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=62&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Nunavut&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=], 2001 Community Profiles</ref><ref>[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table-Tableau.cfm?LANG=Eng&T=101&S=50&O=A], Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories, 2011 and 2006 censuses</ref>\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|24730\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|26745\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|29474\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|31906\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|35944\n}}\n\n==Communities with more than 1,000 people==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Municipality\n! 2011\n! %<br />change\n! 2006\n! %<br />change\n! 2001\n! %<br />change\n|-\n|[[Iqaluit]]{{ref|a|a}}<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=6204003&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Iqaluit&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=6204003&TABID=1 2011 Census Profile Iqaluit]</ref><ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-591/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=6204003&Geo2=PR&Code2=62&Data=Count&SearchText=Iqaluit&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= 